# Data Pipeline Standards

## Event Shape

Every event on the `cv_events` Redpanda topic uses the PostHog capture format.
An engineer at PostHog should open `producer.rs` and immediately recognise their own event structure.

```json
{
  "event": "career_milestone",
  "distinct_id": "dave_carroll",
  "token": "cv_pipeline_v1",
  "timestamp": "2026-05-22T08:23:00Z",
  "properties": { ... }
}
```

The `properties` object contains the actual payload. Never put payload fields at the top level.

## Defined Event Types

Only these event types exist. Do not add new ones without updating `data_models.md` first.

| Event | Writes to |
|---|---|
| `profile_update` | `dim_profile` |
| `career_milestone` | `fact_career_events` |
| `responsibility_added` | `dim_responsibilities` |
| `project_highlight` | `dim_key_projects` |
| `skill_added` | `dim_tech_stack` |
| `education_entry` | `dim_education` |

## Consumer Routing

The consumer matches on the `event` field and dispatches. Each arm calls a dedicated `db::insert_*` function. No catch-all arm that silently swallows unknown events — if an unrecognised event arrives, log it and continue.

```rust
// ✅ correct
match event_type.as_str() {
    "career_milestone"     => db::insert_career_event(&conn, &props)?,
    "responsibility_added" => db::insert_responsibility(&conn, &props)?,
    // ... one arm per event type
    unknown => tracing::warn!("unknown event type: {}", unknown),
}

// ❌ wrong — silent discard
_ => {}
```

## DuckDB Queries

Parameterised queries only. No string interpolation into SQL.

```rust
// ✅ correct
conn.execute(
    "INSERT INTO dim_tech_stack VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)",
    params![id, skill, category, level, sort_order, source],
)?;

// ❌ wrong
conn.execute(
    &format!("INSERT INTO dim_tech_stack VALUES ('{}', ...)", skill),
    [],
)?;
```

Schema creation lives entirely in `db.rs`. `consumer.rs` calls `db::init_schema()` and then `db::insert_*` functions. It does not contain any SQL strings.

## Producer — Messy JSON Handling

`raw_history.json` is intentionally inconsistent (mixed date formats, varying field names, responsibilities as string vs array). The normalisation happens in `producer.rs` using the raw input structs in `models.rs`.

- Date parsing: try known formats in order, fail loudly if none match (don't silently produce a wrong date)
- Field aliasing: use `#[serde(alias = "...")]` on raw structs — don't write manual match chains
- Responsibilities as string: split on `\n`, trim, filter empty lines

The log line `"Bringing order to Chaos, tidying up JSON data"` plays while this runs.

## Firebase

- Fetch Firestore data via REST API using `reqwest` — no Firebase SDK
- The service account key is inside the decrypted `raw_history.json` under `firebase_credentials`
- Fetch `cv/skills`, `cv/highlights` once during the produce phase
- `cv/availability` is **not** fetched during the pipeline — the `/api/profile` Axum handler fetches it live per request
